  <!-- Main Content -->
  <article class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

        <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          If you wake up sneezing, spend the day with itchy eyes, or can't stop rubbing your nose at home, your house might be the problem—not the solution.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Millions of Americans suffer from indoor allergies, and most don't realize that their own home is triggering their symptoms. Dust mites, pet dander, mold spores, and pollen can accumulate in ways you can't see—and standard cleaning often makes it worse.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">The Hidden Allergens in Your Home</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Before we talk about solutions, let's identify the enemy:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Dust Mites</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          These microscopic creatures live in bedding, upholstered furniture, and carpets. They feed on dead skin cells and thrive in warm, humid environments. Their waste particles are one of the most common indoor allergens.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Pet Dander</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          It's not pet hair that triggers allergies—it's the proteins in pet dander (dead skin flakes), saliva, and urine. These particles are incredibly small and can stay airborne for hours.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Mold Spores</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Mold grows anywhere moisture collects: bathrooms, basements, under sinks, around windows. Even small amounts can release thousands of spores into your air.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Pollen</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Outdoor pollen hitches a ride on your clothes, shoes, and pets. It settles on surfaces and can trigger symptoms for days after entering your home.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Why Standard Cleaning Makes Allergies Worse</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Here's the frustrating truth: many common cleaning methods actually spread allergens rather than remove them.
        </p>

        <ul class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8 space-y-3">
          <li><strong>Feather dusters</strong> just move dust from one surface to another (and into the air you breathe).</li>
          <li><strong>Standard vacuums</strong> without HEPA filters blow fine particles back into your room.</li>
          <li><strong>Dry sweeping</strong> sends dust and allergens airborne.</li>
          <li><strong>Scented cleaners</strong> can trigger additional reactions in sensitive individuals.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">The Allergy-Friendly Cleaning Approach</h2>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">1. Use HEPA Filtration Everywhere</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          HEPA (High-Efficiency Particulate Air) filters capture 99.97% of particles as small as 0.3 microns. Use HEPA-filter vacuums and consider HEPA air purifiers in bedrooms and living areas.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">2. Damp Dust, Never Dry Dust</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Damp microfiber cloths trap dust particles instead of spreading them. Work from top to bottom so falling dust lands on surfaces you haven't cleaned yet.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">3. Wash Bedding Weekly in Hot Water</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Dust mites can't survive temperatures above 130°F. Wash sheets, pillowcases, and blankets weekly in hot water. Use allergen-proof covers on mattresses and pillows.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">4. Control Humidity</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Keep indoor humidity between 30-50%. Higher humidity encourages dust mites and mold growth. Use dehumidifiers in damp areas and fix any water leaks immediately.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">5. Clean Air Vents and Filters</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          HVAC systems circulate air throughout your home—including allergens. Clean or replace filters monthly during high-allergen seasons. Have ducts professionally cleaned periodically.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">6. Use Fragrance-Free Products</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Strong fragrances can trigger respiratory symptoms even in people without traditional allergies. Opt for unscented or naturally-scented cleaning products.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Room-by-Room Allergy Priorities</h2>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Bedroom (Highest Priority)</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          You spend 8 hours here every night. Keep it a sanctuary: allergen-proof bedding covers, no carpet if possible, minimal upholstered furniture, and regular HEPA vacuuming.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Bathroom</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The moisture capital of your home. Run exhaust fans during and after showers. Clean weekly with mold-killing products. Check under sinks and around toilets for hidden moisture.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Living Areas</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Upholstered furniture and carpets are allergen magnets. Vacuum weekly (minimum), deep clean quarterly. Consider leather or vinyl furniture which doesn't harbor dust mites.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Kitchen</h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Focus on moisture control around the sink and dishwasher. Empty trash frequently to prevent mold growth. Clean behind and under refrigerator where dust and mold accumulate.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">When to Call the Professionals</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Regular professional deep cleaning can dramatically reduce allergen levels in your home. We recommend:
        </p>

        <ul class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8 space-y-3">
          <li><strong>Quarterly deep cleaning</strong> for allergy sufferers</li>
          <li><strong>Seasonal cleaning</strong> during peak pollen times (spring and fall in Alabama/Tennessee)</li>
          <li><strong>After renovations</strong> which stir up dust and debris</li>
          <li><strong>When moving</strong> into a new home</li>
        </ul>

